\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/cmf.newspace}{New subspace}}
\begin{definition}\label{cmf.newspace}
\uses{character.dirichlet,character.dirichlet.induce,character.dirichlet.modulus,cmf,cmf.character,cmf.cusp_form,cmf.level,cmf.petersson_scalar_product,cmf.weight}
The space $S_k(N,\chi)$ of \hyperref[cmf.cusp_form]{cuspidal} \hyperref[cmf]{modular forms} of \hyperref[cmf.level]{level} $N$, \hyperref[cmf.weight]{weight} $k$, and \hyperref[cmf.character]{character} $\chi$ can be decomposed
\[
S_k(N,\chi) = S_k^{\rm old}(N,\chi) \oplus S_k^{\rm new}(N,\chi)
\]
into old and new subspaces, defined as follows.

If $M$ is a proper divisor of $N$ and $\chi_M$ is a \hyperref[character.dirichlet]{Dirichlet character} of \hyperref[character.dirichlet.modulus]{modulus} $M$ that \hyperref[character.dirichlet.induce]{induces} $\chi$, then for all $d \mid (N/M)$, there is a map from $S_k(M,\chi_M) \to S_k(N,\chi)$ via $f(z) \mapsto f(dz)$.  The span of the images of all of these maps is the \textbf{old subspace} $S_k^{\rm old}(N,\chi) \subseteq S_k(N,\chi)$.

The \textbf{new subspace} $S_k^{\rm new}(N,\chi)$ is the orthogonal complement of $S_k^{\rm old}(N,\chi)$ with respect to the \hyperref[cmf.petersson_scalar_product]{Petersson inner product}.

A basis for the new subspace is given by \hyperref[cmf.newform]{newforms}.
\end{definition}
